{
  "text": "Dietary n-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids (n-3 PUFAs) play an essential role in animal development and maintaining animal health. Ingestion of n-3 PUFAs will lead to their distribution to virtually every cell in the body with effects on neurological development, reproduction, insulin action, innate and acquired immunity [1] . Therefore, majority of the studies aimed at increasing the n-3 PUFAs levels in pork to improve its nutritional quality, by using the diet enriched in either fish oils [CITATION_1] , or plant sources of 18:3 such as linseed [CITATION_2] and canola oil [CITATION_3] . Interestingly, Sousa et al. [CITATION_4] reported that feeding the pigs with a diet including 10 % linseed oil (\u03b1-linolenic acid, C18:3n-3) increased the lean tissue in pigs. Similarly, feeding pigs with a linseed-enriched diet was reported to result in a modest increase in skeletal muscle mass in pigs [CITATION_5] . Moreover, it has been demonstrated that feeding a linseed-enriched diet increased the intramuscular fat content in porcine longissimus muscle [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
